remixed_from.title: A mixin of 2/3 other extruder plate with cable holder.

description.text:
With time I understood that having two static extruder heads at one level is evil. So I removed the right extruder from my Wanhao Duplicator, and offer you a choice: continue getting frustrated by the failed prints because of the second nozzle, OR remove it and use a dummy for hitting the endstop, OR use its place wisely and put a top-bottom powerful 40mm fan on its place!
I also use the cable & PTFE tube holder by elmuchacho, and I properly cut it to fit the new modded extruder assembly.
After this mod my Duplicator works just as I would expect from a good 3D printer. As a bonus, I could push more acceleration out of my printer because now there is no second stepper to move!

description.text:
You should probably check out version 2 instead: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2040624

This is a set of prints that can quickly tell you your printers backlash settings.

I designed it the M3D Micro in mind but there is no reason why it should not work on other cartesian printers as well.

This is by far the quickest method for calibrating backlash I have seen as it produces empirical results in one go instead of using trial and error.

If you own an M3D Micro I recommend using the gcode files I have prepared. If you own another printer you may have to slice the files yourself.

Disclaimer: For my own printer I am fully satisfied with the precision of this method. Others may find that it only brings them in the right ballpark for further tweaking with other methods. And others again may find that results produced with this method are too far off to be useful. Make sure your spool-location does not affect the movement of the print head at all (This last paraphrase probably only applies to the M3D Micro as it is very sensitive)

Printer:

M3d Micro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.350 mm

Infill:

None

Notes:

The files need specific slicing settings as most slicers tend to ignore features that are as flat and slim as these. For this reason I recommend using the gcode files that have been modified and tested with both the official M3D software and M3D Fio/Octoprint.

Turn 90 degrees in the slicer when making the Y-files if you choose to slice an STL file yourself.

How to measure

Very important notice:
In order for this print to work you print bed must be very precisely calibrated. Otherwise the print will come off the bed. My own preferred calibration method for the print bed is this: http://www.thingiverse.com/groups/m3d-the-micro-3d-printer/topic:5062
But print bed calibration is very individual from one type of printer to another, so calibrate the way you prefer.

Adjusting the Y-axis:

  1. In your printer software set Y-backlash to 0 before printing.
  2. Print one of the gcode files that has a Y in the name. Most M3D Micro printers will need the QuickBacklash_Y_0.70-1.69 file. If all of the samples are curvy try the QuickBacklash_Y_0.00-0.99 instead. Watch the print start and remove the extra filament that is extruded in the beginning. It is just to prime the nozzle.
  3. The included files will make 100 samples. You have to study these samples very very carefully. You have to find the sample with the highest possible value that does not curve. We are talking about a curve that only moves 0.01 mm to the side. It sounds impossible to spot. But it is actually doable. I recommend having a ruler in one hand and a flashlight in the other. I never take out my build platform. But if I did, I would probably use a magnifying glass.
  4. When you have located the correct sample, calculate the backlash value using the chart/picture above. The 0.7 file will begin at 0.70 mm in the corner marked with a blob. The 0.0 file will start at 0.00 mm
  5. I think it is a good idea to make three prints and take the average value spotted for each. If one of them is way off disregard it and make another. If in doubt choose the lower value.
  6. Enter the value you found in your printer software.

Adjusting the X-axis:

Similar to the process for the Y-axis. But most M3D Micro printers will need the QuickBacklash_X_0.00-0.99 file. If all the samples are flat try the QuickBacklash_X_0.70-1.69 file instead.

Designed in OpenSCAD.
Sliced in Slic3r and finally the gcode was tweaked in Notepad to work with the Micro's native software.

comments.text:
Backlash is a common problem for many precision machines. You can find lots about it on youtube and the web in general.
In short, it is the fact that a motor will have to turn a little extra when changing direction before the print head actually starts to move. It happens because of mechanical imperfections like loose belts and teeth on gears that aren't perfect.

description.text:
I really liked the design from the original here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26472 however since I have the straight frame on the K8200, I couldn't find a good way to mount, so I remixed this in tinkercad.

I used 5mm threaded bolts on both the bearing holes and mounting on the frame. I added the channel on each side's base to allow minor adjustments on the holder relative to the frame.

EDIT: For an added feeling of security that the roll won't come off the bearings, I added the two large flat washers from the original k8200 filament holder. I have been running the printer day and night and haven't seen any issues. (see pic)

EDIT: After hours of usage, a side cracked at the base where the holder mounts to the frame. I printed this at 20% infill however, for durability and strength, i would recommend printing at 80% infill.

If you like the mod, please let me know if there are any comments / suggestions / ideas for other K8200 parts.

This is the 3D model of the famous spaceship Orion which you can see in the german 60s mini series space patrol Orion.The files are based on the very detailed paper model of Marco Scheloske.I was allowed to use them, when I link to his, in my opinion, very interesting website :
http://technomaniaweb.jimdo.com

I didn`t want to rename all the file names or extend them to far, so you find the translation for the german names underneath.

Orion_A_Grav_Pylonen_8x ==== Antigravity pylons ( used 8x )
Orion_Abstandsscheibe 2x ==== Distance plate ( used 2x )
Orion_Achse_Abschlussplatte ==== Axis with end plate
Orion_Display_Stand ==== Display stand bottom

Orion_Rumpf_Unten ==== Lower hull
Orion_Sensordom ==== Sensordome or sensorarray
Orion_Triebwerkscheibe ==== Engine plate

I suggest to print the antigravity pylons , the lightguns, the holder fot the Orion and the sensordome with much infill because they are tiny and might brake.
All other files are not critical.You can download a sketchup file which shows the mounting.
at the lower hull you have to glue 8 of the antigravity pylons in a 45 deg angle, on the upper hull 3 lightguns in a 120 deg angle.I designed the model because I couldn`t find a printable one and to remember the series which was one of my favourites when I was a boy although I did see the series later in the middle 70s.I hope you have fun !
" Rücksturz zur Erde ! "

title: My Variation on the Voxel Ox

description.text:
This is my variation on the Voxel Ox (http://www.openbuilds.com/builds/voxel-ox-extendable-3d-printer-and-cnc-platform.2418/). I liked their concept of an easily extendable/expandable printer with rigid connections.

The modifications I made are pretty much only to suit standard length parts from Open Builds.
1) The X-Gantry is attached to the back of the vertical-travel Z plates via one corner connector each
2) The top brace is a sideways 20x40 (the 40 in the up/down direction) with motors mounted on top. This allows full length lead screws to be used.
3) Lead screw nuts are mounted to the vertical-travel Z plates. Since the nuts were not tapped perfectly square, the right one is mounted in the middle while the left one is mounted a little further to the rear. Furthermore the motors are moved forward or backward in their slotted holes to help reduce binding.
4) The extruder is mounted 90 degrees to the X-plate. It's attached to a 250mm 20x20 with two corner connectors for each hole in the extruder platform. The 20x20 is attached to the X plate with two corner connectors, one on left, one on the right.
5) I don't have a reel mount solution yet, so my reel sits on the very top, using a clamp for a shaft. the extruder can pull it, but I usually wind some out to help reduce the extra pull on the extruder.

It's a work in progress, but it works pretty well so far for me. I'm starting to get some good prints.

I can post more pictures if you just tell me what you need to see.

Frame printed in cura at 0% infill, 2 nozzle width shell thickness, at 0.2 layer height, no support. The motor hole mounts printed with cura pressfit nicely, I didn't need to sand it although trim runoff, although this could change with any given slicer, or printer, or other factors. Screws need to be screwed in very carefully, as one can strip the plastic easily, especially the less infill percentage used (Adjusting shell thickness will strengthen mounting holes). I will probably design the jjrc camera mount soon, as this allows to the user to disconnect the camera altogether, which is optimal for night flight (I use ic socket to connect camera). Added surface mount led to lcd controller, by running 2 leds in series connected to a 6v source on the board which is connected to the main on/off switch.
This frame overall, was just a test in aerodynamics. While it does show good aerodynamics, the weight even with 0% infill is a bit too much. I was experimenting with trying to create a surface to incorporate the coanda effect, although with a platform this small, in which any additional weight added severely affects the over all performance, it is not optimal. I am now working on a new frame geared for the least weight, while still having decent rigidity.

A rugged az-el mount that converts a telescoping inspection mirror into a bicycle helmet mirror.

We ride our Tour Easy recumbent bikes a lot and depend on our helmet mirrors to keep an eye on traffic. Unfortunately, commercial bicycle helmet mirrors seem to be very stylish, exceedingly fragile, and surprisingly expensive. This mount represents the other extreme: plug-ugly, robust, and (after you have a 3D printer, anyway) cheap. All the plastic bits print in one operation; I used bright yellow filament, but black might be more suitable. Fit a hex nut into the recess in the main body, run a matching screw through the elevation turret, then glue-and-clamp everything together. A setscrew in the tiny hole on top provides just enough friction to keep the elevation mount in place. Cut the third section of the inspection mirror just behind the second joint and epoxy a pan head screw inside the shaft. The shaft fits into the azimuth mount's snout and screws into a small hole due aft of the snout that holds it in place. The double ball joint attaching the mirror to the shaft has far too many fiddly little parts. I epoxied the nut in place and put a thin rubber bushing under the screw head to provide a bit of compliance. That allows small adjustments without any tools while remaining tight. The thin helmet interface plate has a slightly concave surface that matches the helmet curvature well enough to let double-sided foam tape bond them firmly together. These mounts have survived a few thousand miles of bicycling with no visible damage, which is a definite improvement over the commercial mirrors! More details and backstory on my blog:

This is a replacement loader pin for a toy pistol ammo clip reverse engineered from the one my kids broke. It should work equally well in any similar style loader. Depending on the particular style of gun the horizontal pin might need to be filed shorter to fit.

Make the walls on this part 2.4 mm thick with no infill. First layer 0.2mm with a 7 - 10 line brim. All remaining layers 0.1 mm thick. Printing this part requires support material set to at least 30% to provide perfect support for the horizontal pin. It will use hardly any material for the support. The part is quite small. Works well with PLA. Print slowly and use a good part cooling fan. Use filament calibrated both dimensionaly and thermally.

I used the following calibration piece to set the parameters for the filament. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037301

Fitting the part

The loader pin is purposely on the long side to fit multiple styles of gun that use this type of loader. Just file it down to fit your ammo clip. Other than removing the support material no other finishing should be required.

description.text:
The trigger lever on my CM.030 broke when I was converting it to accept LiPo batteries. The original part is made of horrifyingly cheap metal. Over time with use a couple of fine splits had appeared that finally gave in when being carefully removed...

Notes:

Make sure you are getting really good inter-layer bonding. Otherwise the part will not be strong enough.

The part should be rotated so that it is flat against the bed. No support is needed as there is only one really small bridge that should be fine on any printer.

You may need to widen up the holes a tad. The are designed a little tight on purpose as they are supposed to retain pins. In my case I used a 5/64 drill bit. This left a reasonably tight fit. with both pins.

description.text:
This is a keycap puller that will work for a variety of keyboards (mainly mechanical or topre). Use it to remove keycaps in order to swap them or clean your keyboard.

Here is a guide to assembling the keycap puller: https://imgur.com/a/M9XAp. You will need at a minimum 2 large paperclips and some glue.

With regards to 3D printing the file, there are only three things I can think to point out. The first is that there are four 1.25mm diameter holes in the part. Your printer should be able to bridge over them and I recommend against including support for them. The second is that if you print it upward-facing (as it is oriented in the .stl), you will likely need support for the part in the front that is at an incline. The last is that there is no bevel/chamfer so it may feel a little sharp in your hands.

[EDIT 3/23/16: As a reminder, please utilize caution and common sense when you use this keycap puller. Improper use could result in damage to your keyboard, so please refer to a use guide that corresponds to your keyboard before you do anything.]

description.text:
There are several tiny bearings on thingiverse, and I also made an earring featuring pp3dp's bearing, but it was a little bulky: http://thingiverse.com/thing:7127 As the small ones found here usualy need to be assembled, and downscaling the others will not work out, I made one from scratch.
Suprisingly, even 2mm balls print fine. But they kept falling out, even after changing size and depth of the bearing rail. The 5th try then has a flat plate on top and on the bottom.
As the limited resolution of the 3d printer was not capable of printing the sharp edges of the bearing, there allways was enough space for the balls to fall out. Sorry for the bad picture. But yes, it's that tiny and it works- just needs zweezers that crack the little balls loose, using it as a leaver. You might notice the even smaller bearing in one of the pictures. With the thicker plate-mod it would work. Only one of the tiniest actually turned, as the balls where fused to the axis :-) All other turned a few times untill the play was big enough for the balls to roll all over the place. With the "restrictor" plate, you could probably use the smaller balls as they do not fuse so hard to the rest of the print. But as this is a daily project, and I already wasted hours on it, I won't continue it. I'm happy with the print as it is... Still, you COULD print it even smaller, just use one of the smaller versions and put a "restrictor plate" ontop. Under 8mm with three balls would probably work!

Print, break balls loose, done.
Use minimal support angle, else you won't be able to clean it. The zip includes all sketches and files, STLs of more or less unsuccessfull prints, and the version I printed successfully is rev5e_biggerballs_restrictor.stl.
